It is encouraging to see more journalists, academics and thinktanks consider these issues but it won't stop the rot. We need principled leaders with a vision of how the future NHS delivers for everyone, not just those who can pay, or stand to profit from private healthcare.

Critically, there are no extra staff trained privately to deliver private healthcare. The staff will come from the NHS, using their time to deliver care privately instead. At the same time, @BorisJohnson is overseeing atrophy of NHS staff pay and conditions.

The report states that although the private healthcare market is still relatively small, there is confidence in the possibility of double digit growth in the self-pay market over the next three years. There is an incentive to keep NHS waiting lists high. https://t.co/ea87uVQSSB

'Self-pay' private healthcare, for those who can afford it, is booming business. And if you have an interest in growth of the industry,  NHS waiting lists are a convenient driver. (Source: LaingBuisson report July 2022) https://t.co/QMlcOkGMfP
There are well publicised links between senior Tory MPs and the private healthcare industry. These same people and their pals are ultimately in charge of NHS waiting lists.  https://t.co/tr0IOdANdb

It is interesting to optimise flow systems but please I think it's a less important factor than the others
All the top 3 are hard to fix, and essentially require a large amount of investment- (1) public/community health, GP, (2) need more beds, (3) need mainly more/better social care

I don't think we really need to overcomplicate flow. It is predominantly three things,
1. patients in 
2. # beds 
3. patients out

If you get confused, as I do, by the smokescreen put up (not always intentionally) by people on this website, I recommend you read for yourself. Read the reports by @LaingBuisson and releases by @spirehealthcare and @Bupa. Read @FT. Read the excellent work done by @CHPIthinktank

You may disagree with me on the above, that public healthcare is better than private, but please let's have that debate, rather than the strange distraction about whether NHS privatisation is increasing.
If we had adequate public provision, why would people be forced to private?

Public healthcare is cheaper (no profit motive, no shareholders, less admin costs), more transparent (public data governance), more equitable (obviously), and, I would argue, a mark of a basically decent society. It is freedom from fear and should be available to all.

So now we have some facts showing that privatisation is increasing we can move on to whether it matters. Why is private healthcare a bad thing? Maybe let's turn it round and let's say why public healthcare is a good thing.
9/ Mayo and Cleveland, US healthcare clinics with big international reputations, have moved into the expanding UK private market. https://t.co/Wk3QNeP5d7
8/ More people are now paying for private hip and knee operations since they were first introduced in the 60s and 70s, reports @FT https://t.co/4quaOs85LU https://t.co/gbp9PFEDV7

7/ Private healthcare firms have done big business with the NHS during the pandemic,¬†worth¬†around ¬£2bn. In May, the IHPN¬†said¬†its members carried out 3.2m NHS procedures in the previous year, including more than 160,000 for cancer and cardiology https://t.co/OrMdIcLwoT

6/ Although private health insurance remains relatively low, Compare the Market¬†said¬†there had been an average 40% increase in year-on-year sales. Around 4 million people in the UK now have private medical insurance, mainly through their employer https://t.co/OrMdIcLwoT
5/  @LaingBuisson also report that digital targeting of customers by private healthcare companies is being seen as an increasingly successful for recruiting the naive sick https://t.co/lH9othONZD
4/ Spire, which has 40 hospitals nationwide, reported an 80% rise in self-pay revenue in LQ 2021 compared to LQ 2019 https://t.co/JIqp6ZRaSQ

3/ Self-pay is a lucrative part of private healthcare industry, set to grow steadily. It remains a key target for private healthcare investors around the NHS. See @LaingBuisson report 2021: https://t.co/UF78k5Nq48 https://t.co/viXeYAjYQL

2/ Most private hospital activity happens in London. One of the reasons we don't know about NHS Trusts' costs in treating private patients is because many won't tell us. 73 (around 60%) didn't respond to an FoI in research done in 2018 by @CHPIthinktank https://t.co/7mCwM3zg0b

1/ We can all agree that privatisation is increasing. 
Below is a. rise in trust private spend, and b. rise in trust/commissioner private spend from 7 --> 12% (blue columns). Figures @NuffieldTrust https://t.co/Rba7yKMCzx

Yes, I know GPs have always been 'private' (though clearly there's a big difference between a group of doctors vs. a US healthcare Corp running your local surgery). 
And yes, I know social care is as big, if not a bigger issue. My focus here is hospital care in England.

Second general point is the accusation that 'NHS privatisation' is 'unfalsifiable'. There's another pretty basic problem here. There are a number of facts which support that 'the NHS' or 'healthcare' is being privatised. Facts are true and not false things.

The first, and so basic a point, to make, is that obviously there will never be a 'meteor impact' privatisation of the NHS, ala Royal Mail. This would be, it is generally agreed political suicide due to the public's value of the service. This straw man needs to burn.
